Notebook[{
Cell["Projective Layer Tutorial", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"c65bce9a-76e3-4cc9-85ac-3c0576b7b175"],

Cell["\<\
A walkthrough of synthetic projective geometry on graphs: pencils, rays, \
common lines, common points, and the Whitehead projective-plane test, with \
runnable examples on paths, cycles, grids, and the Levi graph of the Fano \
plane.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c6c71a2a-940a-4aaa-9fd4-4b8be1084e17"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"7ee72381-f6fb-4290-b684-4bf89b5174e0"],

Cell["Load the paclet.", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"c93d6185-6ee5-4752-ba67-84dd1b57f282"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"739c63c5-8e22-4133-a1d0-8310ca77d2d4"],

Cell["Pencils at a vertex", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"0c2b462b-c7a8-49ea-b710-349a08989478"],

Cell["\<\
A pencil at vertex O is the set of all maximal-geodesic direction classes \
through O. The number of directions -- the pencil cardinality -- is a graph \
invariant of the pair (G, O).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"bafe2b1a-f94a-474a-bde8-7f4becd4b552"],

Cell["\<\
The simplest case: a path graph. Every interior vertex sits on exactly one \
canonical maximal geodesic (the full path), so the pencil cardinality is 1.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"27a9896e-4fea-46ee-9835-7af3cb04eaf1"],

Cell["FindPencil[PathGraph[Range[7]], 4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"875a24a9-6f85-4005-af17-d4e44213417e"],

Cell["\<\
The result is wrapped: an InfraPencil holding one constituent InfraRay (one \
direction class), which in turn carries the maximal geodesics through vertex \
4 sharing that direction.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3dabb275-349d-4469-b759-7d8119d8d8f7"],

Cell["Read the cardinality directly:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"02a640e9-e6b9-4b65-83f2-404612d52066"],

Cell["PencilCardinality[PathGraph[Range[7]], 4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"277f0d85-252b-490f-b16e-79756a6e07a0"],

Cell["\<\
A more interesting case: a cycle. From any vertex you can reach every other \
vertex along multiple maximal geodesics; the pencil cardinality counts \
canonical lines through O, deduplicated by orientation.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"beb483c5-4f38-4cf0-b7aa-43b0c948cf69"],

Cell["FindPencil[CycleGraph[6], 1]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"448cd878-8728-4366-a159-bb7f417e19d8"],

Cell["\<\
Four direction classes -- the pencil cardinality is 4. The antipodal vertex 4 \
is reachable along two of those four classes (the clockwise and \
counter-clockwise half-cycles), so 4 belongs to two directions simultaneously.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"31551e4b-119b-40f1-a401-6b22d41a22ef"],

Cell["\<\
Verify by counting: how many lines in the pencil contain vertex 4?\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"59485cb6-2847-42ad-951a-8b32727ed784"],

Cell["\<\
Count[FindPencil[CycleGraph[6], 1][\"Rays\"], ray_ /; MemberQ[ray, 4]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"68d906fc-d6a0-45f3-91d1-bedf0ef415bb"],

Cell["Visualizing a pencil", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"64fc238a-3f03-4b97-bb51-30d848b191c9"],

Cell["\<\
The pencil renders diffusely. The apex O gets natural emphasis because it \
appears in every constituent ray, so the count-weighting raises its opacity \
automatically.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5a10dfa5-c6e5-4190-926c-fb8e2b8df1da"],

Cell["\<\
InfraSceneHighlight[CycleGraph[6], {FindPencil[CycleGraph[6], 1] -> Red}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8a8430d2-8ac8-436e-b1d3-b7d79a1c8a19"],

Cell["Combining the pencil with the apex highlighted explicitly:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"3485ab70-444f-4aa3-af8c-86ea10785260"],

Cell["\<\
InfraSceneHighlight[CycleGraph[6], {InfraPoint[{1}] -> Black, \
FindPencil[CycleGraph[6], 1] -> Red}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"0773acd9-afa2-44c8-a020-606bd66933a6"],

Cell["Rays in a single direction", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"70b2ad5e-f07c-4117-bb37-78bae78a1671"],

Cell["\<\
FindRay isolates the lines through O sharing direction with v. When the \
underlying FindLine is multi-valued, the ray multi-realises.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7d48d40f-95c7-459f-9374-78ce8d955cc6"],

Cell["FindRay[CycleGraph[6], 1, 4, All]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"5f71e537-c258-40d2-a3a7-7fc50877b986"],

Cell["\<\
Two realisations -- the same direction (origin 1, antipode 4), reached via \
two distinct geodesic half-cycles.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1d479707-9cc7-40ad-8244-f838d6d43b73"],

Cell["Render both realisations of one ray:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"b3c4bbc0-81ea-433b-93a9-f7a6f0568540"],

Cell["\<\
InfraSceneHighlight[CycleGraph[6], {FindRay[CycleGraph[6], 1, 4, All] -> \
Blue}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"bc389339-5211-4fb7-aae8-c1bf4ff2250c"],

Cell["Common lines and common points", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d82eb279-6913-4157-ab01-775bed325be6"],

Cell["\<\
The dual postulates: lines containing all of a set of vertices, and vertices \
on all of a set of lines.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4cc06a0b-8975-4423-9431-72de7bbe3750"],

Cell["FindCommonLine[GridGraph[{3, 3}], {1, 5, 9}, All]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"016535d7-753c-4905-b4a4-c688bd88cafd"],

Cell["\<\
The grid's main diagonal is a common line through {1, 5, 9}; the \
anti-diagonal is too if you list {3, 5, 7}.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3b99341f-1d43-4b95-991e-443074e2afc8"],

Cell["\<\
FindCommonPoint dualises: given a list of lines, return their shared vertices.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"0c91aa96-739e-4df7-8fc4-797dfc24046c"],

Cell["\<\
FindCommonPoint[GridGraph[{3, 3}], {{1, 5, 9}, {3, 5, 7}}, All]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8fe3e776-5ba6-496b-a0e4-7c4607b7f14e"],

Cell["Both diagonals share only the centre vertex 5.", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"64efbee3-d685-4c49-88b1-a6a07e99e638"],

Cell["Multi-anchor spread", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"3865512e-e9d3-4f72-8cb5-f8ebed3a29ab"],

Cell["\<\
Find* in the projective layer accepts Infra* anchors. The behaviour is \
union-conjunction over wrapped lists (FindCommonLine / FindCommonPoint) and \
Cartesian over individual anchors (FindRay / FindPencil).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2231b793-111a-4628-9d3e-b395beb61ea5"],

Cell["\<\
Multi-anchor common-line search: take the union of vertex realisations and \
find canonical lines through it.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"e48e2a38-f93c-4dad-b29e-2b5b55ed9f0d"],

Cell["\<\
FindCommonLine[GridGraph[{3, 3}], {InfraPoint[{1, 5}], 9}, All]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"9b8aaae7-d687-4328-8bb6-001a5c8814a7"],

Cell["Multi-origin pencil: union the constituent rays.", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"3eb88bff-4419-4ebc-a45c-6d3c8404014a"],

Cell["FindPencil[CycleGraph[6], InfraPoint[{1, 4}]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"e2526c0d-d3e8-453d-b637-b7f07708c40e"],

Cell["The Whitehead projective-plane axioms", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"967d9c54-4679-47cd-9220-ffa84e6025e6"],

Cell["\<\
A graph is a projective plane in the synthetic-incidence sense if its lines \
(canonical maximal geodesics) satisfy the three Whitehead axioms plus a \
non-degeneracy clause.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"facfd900-d653-46db-a209-ec2bff2a2ad9"],

Cell["W1 -- every line has at least three vertices.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"6e51e945-a4df-42de-9e1d-b93ac7ff2d69"],

Cell["\<\
W2 -- through any two distinct vertices there is exactly one line (geodetic \
property).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"80cd745d-411a-44fa-808c-74a3ed1d5ff3"],

Cell["\<\
W3 -- the four-vertex axiom: if some line through {A,B} meets some line \
through {C,D}, then some line through {A,C} meets some line through {B,D}.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7dd29c8f-b167-4d57-87c7-c39297a54d3e"],

Cell["\<\
A path graph fails W1 (its endpoints sit on a line of length 2, only two \
vertices on that line):\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"81c5713f-4efe-439b-be29-561970a25fd5"],

Cell["\<\
{WhiteheadW1Q[PathGraph[Range[5]]], \
ProjectivePlaneGraphQ[PathGraph[Range[5]]]}\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"42c025eb-4d95-42e1-8fd6-eb0a92994d63"],

Cell["\<\
A complete graph on four vertices fails W1 too -- every edge is a line of \
length 2.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"d97e7654-b3e1-4260-9a21-22f8df313b75"],

Cell["\<\
{WhiteheadW1Q[CompleteGraph[4]], ProjectivePlaneGraphQ[CompleteGraph[4]]}\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"91c2d8b6-cc5b-406a-b203-12f7f2ee8106"],

Cell["\<\
The Levi graph of the Fano plane is the smallest finite projective plane (7 \
points, 7 lines, 3 points per line, 3 lines per point). Its incidence \
structure can be encoded as a bipartite graph; the synthetic test \
ProjectivePlaneGraphQ is O(|V|^4), so we keep the example small.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5349397e-4011-49f2-8346-f9fcf2f91a42"],

Cell["\<\
fano = Graph[{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, p7}, {1 <-> p1, 1 \
<-> p2, 1 <-> p3, 2 <-> p1, 2 <-> p4, 2 <-> p5, 3 <-> p1, 3 <-> p6, 3 <-> p7, \
4 <-> p2, 4 <-> p4, 4 <-> p6, 5 <-> p2, 5 <-> p5, 5 <-> p7, 6 <-> p3, 6 <-> \
p4, 6 <-> p7, 7 <-> p3, 7 <-> p5, 7 <-> p6}, GraphLayout -> \
\"BipartiteEmbedding\"]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"adb43695-8506-462d-b288-3650a2a9e5fc"],

Cell["WhiteheadW1Q[fano]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"c5e494de-646e-46c8-aeaf-f9dcea4d9ba7"],

Cell["Uniqueness predicates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"e93639f7-aaf1-4073-9a96-32c2e13260cf"],

Cell["\<\
The Unique*Q variants check the strict single-witness version of each \
existential predicate.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4fb2e33b-45d8-4f1d-bbf9-2ed112be6dd3"],

Cell["UniquePencilQ -- every direction at O has exactly one line.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"6c6c9446-d85f-4c57-97d1-e3fff49f673e"],

Cell["\<\
UniqueCollinearQ -- exactly one canonical line contains every listed vertex.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b73ea891-86b0-445a-a331-4a62ee89c143"],

Cell["\<\
UniqueConcurrentQ -- exactly one common vertex across the listed lines.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"2733c0c2-d868-44e9-b390-9044001dd9b0"],

Cell["UniquePencilQ[PathGraph[Range[7]], 4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"05df25d3-2b30-401e-bc5e-f2fbce64cc33"],

Cell["UniquePencilQ[CycleGraph[6], 1]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"16654d6c-5084-4905-b2af-30d32ef6e885"],

Cell["\<\
The cycle's antipode direction admits two geodesics, so the pencil is not \
single-valued.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b55d5aa2-4dad-446c-8804-6c825d17988e"],

Cell["UniqueCollinearQ[PathGraph[Range[5]], {1, 3}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"26a75032-dcaa-4ef2-a7e9-85f9ce2e0e8a"],

Cell["UniqueConcurrentQ[GridGraph[{3, 3}], {{1, 5, 9}, {3, 5, 7}}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"18599685-f4d4-4903-aa1f-3f9d210c5ae6"],

Cell["Where this connects to the rest of the paclet", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"92690ca8-8cd6-4dbb-8d26-22ca1d8d8ec7"],

Cell["\<\
The projective layer is incidence-only -- it depends on FindLine for the \
canonical-line enumeration but ignores metric quantities like distance, \
angle, or curvature. This gives a clean separation:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8e5f25b0-89ca-4e1d-a87c-589a0bd873b2"],

Cell["\<\
The Euclidean layer (FindPoint, FindSegment, FindLine, FindShell, FindCircle, \
FindParallel) supplies the metric primitives.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7f980d57-bc41-4fad-9547-c75c507f2ca8"],

Cell["\<\
The projective layer (this tutorial) restricts attention to incidence \
relations, recovering the abstract structure of points and lines.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"badbf0bf-9b1c-40bb-b63c-75892f29b089"],

Cell["\<\
The affinization direction (planned) glues the two: pick a centre and unit \
segments per direction to recover affine \\u2124^k coordinates from the \
pencil.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7d78e61c-a8f6-45bd-88b3-c4c71b48530a"],

Cell["\<\
The next batches in the projective roster -- cross sections, Desargues, \
Pappus, harmonic conjugates -- build on the foundation laid here.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"81451eb7-3f91-465c-ad7c-c0dff2beb225"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"31ca7fb2-aa7d-401b-bdb4-422b305e2548"],

Cell["\<\
ProjectiveLayerGuide -- categorical overview of every symbol in the layer.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"0171e53c-4eb1-4eb0-af80-e731dea97c2f"],

Cell["\<\
EuclideanLayerGuide -- the metric primitives FindLine and friends that the \
projective layer depends on.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"46f4ecf7-8885-4860-b9f0-2b8dafe6d89c"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiLayerGuide -- the betweenness/equidistance axiomatisation that \
complements the synthetic-incidence reading here.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c9539e33-0aa6-4d40-9ef5-17e0d06fee3e"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"fc461769-ac51-4c91-9587-7ba4411bf693"],

Cell["\<\
Whitehead, The Axioms of Projective Geometry, Cambridge University Press \
1906, https://archive.org/details/cu31924001520455\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ea40edca-746d-44f4-a423-704863ab0046"],

Cell["\<\
Hartshorne, Foundations of Projective Geometry, W. A. Benjamin 1967.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"aa03a0ab-c79a-4673-87f5-67d62e4d24a4"],

Cell["\<\
Beutelspacher and Rosenbaum, Projective Geometry: From Foundations to \
Applications, Cambridge University Press 1998.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e197ac36-6c9e-4b6e-8489-43655c5650a1"],

Cell["Coxeter, Projective Geometry, 2nd ed., Springer 1987.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b08cd91d-6a6e-4382-b709-14a92dc76f44"]
},
